[Relevant CDC links include https://www.cdc.gov/flu/spotlights/2021-2022/two-variant-infections.htm.

When people are infected with influenza A viruses that are known to be genetically similar to viruses circulating in swine, these viruses are called "variant viruses" and denoted with a letter "v". Human infections with A(H1N1)v, A(H1N2)v, and A(H3N2)v viruses have been detected in the United States (see https://www.cdc.gov/flu/swineflu/variant.htm). The FluView Interactive Novel Flu A tool (https://gis.cdc.gov/grasp/fluview/Novel_Influenza.html) reflects the most current case counts for variant virus infections reported in the United States since 2010.

Novel viruses are detected with methods available for detection of currently circulating human influenza viruses at state public health laboratories (for example, real-time reverse transcriptase polymerase chain reaction [RT-PCR]). Confirmation that an influenza A virus represents a novel virus is performed by CDC's influenza laboratory. Once a novel virus has been identified by CDC, confirmation may be made by public health laboratories following CDC-recommended protocols for that specific virus, or by laboratories using an FDA-authorized test specific for detection of that novel influenza virus.

During 2021, 14 cases of human infection with swine origin variant influenza viruses have been reported. Out of these, 7 cases of influenza A H1N1v (Wisconsin 3, Iowa 3, North Dakota 1) and 3 confirmed cases of influenza A H3N2v (Wisconsin 1, Iowa 1, Ohio 1) have been reported thus far.

Most infections with variant viruses have occurred in children (persons 18 or younger), and most cases have reported direct or indirect exposure to swine before onset of illness. Limited transmission from close contact with an infected person has been observed in some investigations of human infections with variant viruses, but sustained human-to-human transmission has not been documented. - Mod.UBA

